8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 PART I. STANLY COMMUNITY COLLEGE OFF MAIN CAMPUS CULINARY
11 PROGRAM
12 SECTION 1.1. Section 9.15 of S.L. 2017-57 is repealed.
13
14 PART II. GULLAH GEECHEE HERITAGE TRAIL
15 SECTION 2.1. The General Assembly authorizes the Gullah Geechee
16 Greenway/Blueway Heritage Trail (Heritage Trail) in Brunswick County. The State shall
17 support, promote, encourage, and facilitate the establishment of trail segments on State park lands
18 and on lands of other federal, State, local, and private landowners. On segments of the Heritage
19 Trail that cross property controlled by agencies or owners other than the State, the laws, rules,
20 and policies of those agencies or owners shall govern the use of the property.
21
22 PART III. STATE PROPERTY TRANSFER TO THE TOWN OF BURGAW
23 SECTION 3.1. The State of North Carolina shall convey to the Town of Burgaw,
24 for consideration of one dollar ($1.00), all its rights, titles, and interests in approximately 11 acres
25 of the approximately 355.73 acre parcel identified with Land Asset ID 6095 in the inventory of
26 State-owned land maintained by the Department of Administration pursuant to G.S. 143-341.
27 This is the same property identified with PIN Number 3229-04-1665-0000, as seen in the Office
28 of the Tax Administrator in Pender County, and is described in part in Deed Book 211, Page 279
29 and Deed Book 922, Page 191 in the Pender County Register of Deeds. The Department of
30 Administration, in consultation with the Town of Burgaw, shall determine specifically which
31 portion of the land described in this section shall be transferred pursuant to this section.
32 SECTION 3.2. The conveyance pursuant to Section 3.1 of this Part is subject to a
33 reversionary interest reserved by the State. The property shall be conveyed to the Town of
34 Burgaw for so long as it is utilized for public purposes.
*H23-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 3.3. The State of North Carolina shall convey the real property described
2 in Section 3.1 of this Part "as is" and "where is" without warranty. The State makes no
3 representations or warranties concerning the title to the property, the boundaries of the property,
4 the uses to which the property may be put, zoning, local ordinances, or any physical,
5 environmental, health, and safety conditions relating to the property. All costs associated with
6 the conveyance of the property shall be borne by the Town of Burgaw.
7 SECTION 3.4. The conveyance of the State's rights, titles, and interests in the real
8 property described in Section 3.1 of this Part shall be exempt from the provisions of Article 7 of
9 Chapter 146 of the General Statutes. The conveyance shall comply with the provisions of Article
10 16 of Chapter 146 of the General Statutes, provided that the provisions of G.S. 146-74 shall not
11 apply.
12
13 PART IV. AUTHORIZE ADDING SOUTH FORK PASSAGE STATE TRAIL TO THE
14 STATE PARKS SYSTEM
15 SECTION 4.1. The General Assembly finds:
16 (1) The proposed South Fork Passage Trail corridor offers numerous economic
17 benefits by expanding and enhancing the existing tourism industry. The
18 diverse hydrology of the river in the corridor includes shoals, flatwater, class
19 II rapids, and river tributaries that support a variety of recreational uses.
20 (2) The South Fork Passage Trail corridor is home to Spencer Mountain, the third
21 highest peak in the Charlotte region, and the corridor passes through terrain
22 that is emblematic of the Piedmont region of the State.
23 (3) The South Fork Passage Trail corridor also contains ecologically important
24 habitat, including diverse wetlands, hardwood forests, and grasslands, that
25 support numerous State and federal threatened or endangered species.
26 (4) The creation of a 60-mile hiking and paddling trail connecting Jacob Fork
27 Park in Catawba County through Betty G. Ross Park in Lincoln County to
28 George Poston Park, Goat Island Park, and Daniel Stowe Botanical Garden in
29 Gaston County would expand existing recreational offerings and support
30 ongoing efforts to conserve the South Fork of the Catawba River watershed.
31 SECTION 4.2. The General Assembly authorizes the Department of Natural and
32 Cultural Resources (Department) to add the South Fork Passage Trail in Catawba, Lincoln, and
33 Gaston Counties to the State Parks System as a State trail, as provided in G.S. 143B-135.54(b).
34 The trail, which will run alongside the South Fork River, shall begin at the confluence of the
35 Henry Fork and Jacob Fork at Jacob Fork Park and end at the boundary between the State and
36 South Carolina on Lake Wylie.
37 SECTION 4.3. The Department shall support, promote, encourage, and facilitate the
38 establishment of trail segments on State Park lands and on lands of other federal, State, local, and
39 private landowners. On segments of the South Fork Passage State Trail that cross property
40 controlled by agencies or owners other than the Department's Division of Parks and Recreation,
41 the laws, rules, and policies of those agencies or owners shall govern the use of the property.
42 SECTION 4.4. The requirement of G.S. 143B-135.54(b) that additions be
43 accompanied by adequate appropriations for land acquisition, development, and operations shall
44 not apply to the authorization set forth in this Part; provided, however, that the State may receive
45 donations of appropriate land and may purchase other needed lands for the South Fork Passage
46 State Trail with existing funds in the Land and Water Fund, the Parks and Recreation Trust Fund,
47 the Complete the Trails Fund, the federal Land and Water Conservation Fund, and other available
48 sources of funding.
49
